## **Better Architecture Options:**

### **Option 1: Backend does ALL filtering** (most common)
• Backend: Apply confidence threshold, limit results, sort
• Frontend: Just display what backend sends (no filtering logic)

### **Option 2: Frontend does ALL filtering** (for dynamic UX)
• Backend: Send all raw correlations
• Frontend: Filter/sort/limit based on user interactions (sliders, dropdowns)

### **Option 3: Hybrid** (current mess)
• Both do filtering = duplicate logic + confusion

## **Why This Happened:**
The frontend was built when backend had simpler filtering, then backend got enhanced but frontend
kept its own logic. Classic technical debt.

## **Best Practice:**
For your use case, Option 1 (backend filtering) is better because:
• Users don't need real-time filtering controls
• Reduces data transfer
• Single source of truth for business logic
• Simpler frontend code

The current setup works but creates maintenance headaches when logic changes need to be updated 
in two places.

