> Perfect! I've identified and fixed the issue. Here's what was happening:

## The Problem
The backend was updated to return correlation insights in a new object format:
javascript
{
  triggers: [],
  helpers: [], 
  trends: []
}


But the frontend useCorrelations.js hook was still expecting an array and trying to use .filter()
directly on the correlations data, causing the "n.filter is not a function" error.

## The Solution
I updated the useCorrelations.js hook to:

1. Handle both formats: Added a compatibility layer that detects whether the backend returns an 
array (old format) or object (new format)

2. Convert to array: When the new object format is received, it flattens all correlations from 
triggers, helpers, and trends arrays into a single allCorrelations array

3. Maintain compatibility: All existing .filter() operations now work on allCorrelations instead 
of the raw correlations response

4. Preserve functionality: All the existing grouping, filtering, and statistical functions 
continue to work as expected

## Key Changes
• Added allCorrelations array that handles both backend formats
• Updated all .filter(), .some(), and array operations to use allCorrelations
• Return allCorrelations as the main correlations data to maintain API compatibility
• No breaking changes to components that use this hook

The fix has been committed and pushed, which will trigger an automatic deployment. The error 
should be resolved once the new frontend code is deployed and the browser cache is cleared.

